"Ladislaw" is supposed to be Polish? W≈Çadys≈Çaw is a traditional Polish first name, always spelled with that initial W. To see it without that W, and as a surname, too, is mighty weird. I wonder if any Polish 19th century novel has a (half) English character called John Illiam or Robert Teven...

I still find it funny how English speakers, who pretty much write down their language however they see fit, and have actual words that are pronounced differently even though they are spelled the same (polish and Polish, say), think us Poles have loco spelling. For us, what you see is what you get - if it's spelled a certain way there is only ever one way to pronounce it.

